metadata.name: E=B; #126
metadata.description:
- Last day with the dying planet -

A sentimental start.

It is the last day of this planet, you once lived and shared so many meaningful memories.

Take a last good look at the places of the planet. Look to the far side. You see people were leaving already. But you loved the planet so much that you dare to risk and stay a bit longer before you leave.

This moment becomes bottomless. Landscapes glitter vividly with altered gradients, fog emits at the far end of the land, and Energy leaks and escapes from the core, thru the cracks in form of aurora structure.

It is a mix of sadness, grief, missing, and anxiety.
It is the end.
It is breathtaking.
It makes you hesitate.

// About the scene
The planet was vast.
You may experience Rocky Sierra, Fluidy Mountains, Wide Dunes, and even Calm Ocean.

The Breakdown
In the rare case, you might be able to see a highly pixelated/extreme wide/flat landscape with finely emitted aurora, which is considered a rare scene. i.e. absolute strength of light vs breakdown of limited matters.

// About the presentation style
The Texture & The Drawing : Heavily inspired by pencil sketching techniques that emphasize shading and outline relationship towards an angular light source.

Apply color scheme from other Astro objects to give an alternative look for the planet.

The Animation Sequence: Custom storytelling algorithms combine the formation of the aurora, landscape, and scene detail all in a timeline. The resulting sequential narrative style illustrates the history of the landscape and the aurora formation.

Not just giving the collector the final look but also sharing the cause and reason of such composition.

The Tiny Zoom: A tiny zoom-out movement is implemented in the piece to echo the theme of the piece. i.e. leaving and departing the planet.

// About the Music
Two theme songs were made for this piece.

Theme I: [Solitude]
Theme II: [Fragmented]

Both songs were made to present the process of departure: the sleep of the planet and the awakening of the observer.

// Metaphor
We face departure and arrival all the time. They might be the best or the worst memories of our life. Whether you are willing to or not.

The ending is an ongoing process and on the other side of the Ending comes the beginning.

It is ok to be sentimental.

// Control
Best viewed in large and wide proportion.
(Open in new window)

[S] - save the scene once the drawing stops
[L] - leave and take a look at other places
[Mouse Click] - click twice to initiate music. then click one to mute/show


- 與垂死星球的最後一天 -

從感傷開始。

這是你曾經生活在的星球之最後一天，你們的關係將要結束，許多有意義的回憶也將封印成回憶。

看看遠方。其他人已經開始離開了。
你還留著，想好好看看這個星球。

你請願冒險，也要在離開之前多停留一段時間。

此刻像是無限。景觀隨著漸變的顏色而變得更加生動，在陸地的遠端散發出最後的火霧，能量從核心洩漏，以極光狀的結構從裂縫中逸出。

它是悲傷、內疚、思念和焦慮的混合體。
這是結束。
但又嘆為觀止。
讓你猶豫不決。

// 關於現場
這個星球曾經很大
您會經歷到寂靜的岳峰、流動的山脈、寬闊的沙丘以及平靜的海洋。

罕見的一刻 - 物質崩壞
在極少數情況下，您可能會看到極寬/平坦/鋸齒化的景觀與高像素細膩的極光並存，即光的絕對強度與有限的物質瓦解。

// 關於演示風格
紋理與繪畫風格 : 深受鉛筆素描技術的啟發，這些技術強調與角光源的陰影和輪廓關係。

應用其他天文物體的配色方案，為地球提供另一種外觀。

動畫序列 : 自定義敘事算法將極光、風景和場景細節的形成全部結合在一個時間軸中。由此產生的順序敘述風格，說明了景觀的歷史和極光的形成。

不僅給收藏家最終的外觀，而且還分享了這種構圖的原因和原因。

小變焦 : 作品中實施了微小的縮小運鏡，以呼應作品的主題 - 離開。

// 關於音樂
為作品製作了兩首主題曲。

主題一：【獨】
主題二：【碎】

兩首歌表達/呈現離開的過程：星球的沉睡和觀察者的覺醒。

// 隱喻
不管你願不願意，我們無時無刻都面臨著離去和到來。離去前它們是我們一生中最美好/最糟糕的回憶。

結局是一維，離開是二維的，另一端叫作開始。

覺得感傷是ok 的。

// 控制
但在大寬視窗下視覺效果最好
(Open in new window)

[S] - 繪圖停止後存取畫作
[L] - 離開去其他地方看看
[鼠標單擊] - 單擊兩次以啟動音樂。 然後單擊一個靜音/顯示

metadata.name: Bonsai Bonanza #757
metadata.description:
In previous works, I was attracted by the idea of ​​the domestication of plants.
According to Wikipedia, the purposes of bonsai are primarily contemplation for the viewer, and the pleasant exercise of effort and ingenuity for the grower. By contrast with other plant cultivation practices, bonsai is not intended for production of food or for medicine. Instead, bonsai practice focuses on long-term cultivation and shaping of one or more small trees growing in a container.
I pressume that the main intention is aesthetic. The beauty. Because we love beautiful things.
It is very interesting how we modify certain creatures for our sake of satisfaction.

May this collection brings you good fortune.

metadata.name: Polar Grid #161
metadata.description:
Polar Grid is part of the fxhash live minting experience at Proof of People, London 2022.

This is a study of color, motion, and composition, and an homage to cinema as an artform. Colorful shapes overlap and pulse in a ever repeating dance. An abstracted movie experience. Each color palette in the series (except one) is inspired by a different film director (if you want a real challenge, see how many you can guess without looking at the feature names).

The palettes were extracted from movie stills or movie posters and fine tuned by hand. As often, I have to thank independent tool makers for their indirect help. My gratitude goes to David Aerne for FarbVélo and Fabrizio Bianchi for Coolors.

The code for Polar Grid is based on early iterations of what ultimately became my carat series. Both projects come from the same fascination for color as a system, even though I used a different approach here. You could call this a carat prequel.

The animation is done using a technique called polar noise. This makes it so the motion of all elements ends up repeating in the same amount of time. This is useful for generating motion that loops perfectly while still appearing organic. In this particular case, the animation repeats every π × 100 seconds.

A challenge in building any generative system is to find the right balance between coherence and variety. I designed the system with the large edition size in mind. During development I generated hundreds of iterations and tweaked my code to make sure that every iteration is truly unique and fits the overall aesthetic of the collection.

I truly hope you will enjoy your own little abstract movie.

— Raphaël de Courville


Released: July 6th 2022

Medium: p5.js, html canvas, css

Reference: sk220621


**About the artist**

Raphaël de Courville is a generative artist, streamer, and educator. His artistic work is an exploration of generative systems, patterns, interactivity, and time. Born in Paris, he lives and works in Berlin.


**Instructions**

- Click/Tap or press SPACEBAR to play and pause the animation

In Fullscreen mode (desktop only):
- Press UP or DOWN arrows to adjust image quality (Note: this can affect performance)
- Press F to hide/show the browser UI

metadata.name: Breakers #150
metadata.description:
Companion project to Neural Collapse (#15780), for the collectors of my previous efforts.
A study on the repetition and stacking of a simple dynamic structure, this time inside a cylinder.

Everything procedurally generated at runtime.

Interactivity : 
- You can click on each individual breaker to open or close them. The problem is it will toggle others.
- Press and hold the mouse button to slightly move the viewpoint. The previous interaction not being disabled while doing that, you get some switching all over the place as a bonus bug/feature.

- Press "a" to increase quality of the antialiasing (3 levels), at the cost of performances. If you don't like jaggies and your machine can take it.
- Export a PNG capture at various resolutions by pressing the number keys 1 to 9 (top row or numpad, and only in live mode, after pressing "open"). Resolutions ranges from 720 to 7680 pixels. I recommend starting with "4".

GPU recommended. Best performances on Chrome in general.

metadata.name: a necessary reaction #12
metadata.description:
This piece has an interesting (to me) history. I originally started by trying to clone my IRL physical painting style in Midjourney. I got very close, then I had the idea to make a generative piece that could recreate the Midjourney recreation of my physical paintings. 

As is the nature of things, this result has departed quite a bit from my original intentions. You can scroll through the last two weeks of my Twitter feed to follow the entire process and see the original source. During the course of this writing process, crypto crashed, and the piece got darker and darker. 

There are certain combinations which will result on a matte black on matte black image (that I've taken to calling "carbon mode." A mint is in carbon mode when both palettes are 1, with a gesture on top. This is definitely the darkest mint I've done for FxHash, or even in general, and matches my mood as I watch my net worth drill to the core of the Earth. I am, however, an optimist, and I fully expect to look back on this month and laugh. Hopefully in the not-too-distant future.

metadata.name: this is a bird #56
metadata.description:
"Imagine an infant lying in its cradle and the window is open and into the room comes something marvelous, mysterious, glittering, shedding light of many colors, movement, sound, a transformative hierophany of integrated perception... and the child is enthralled.

And then the mother comes into the room and she says to the child 'That's a bird, baby. That's a bird.' Instantly, the complex wave of the angel peacock iridescent transformative mystery is collapsed into the word. All mystery is gone.

The child learns 'this is a bird, this is a bird'. And by the time we’re five or six years old all the mystery of reality has been carefully tiled over with words."
-- Terence McKenna
